	<div id="page-body" class="page-body">
		<div class="page-number">Page <strong>1</strong> of <strong>1</strong></div>
					<div class="post">
				<h3>Use of lineman's butt set dial.</h3>
				<div class="date">Posted: <strong>Tue Apr 07, 2020 1:48 am</strong></div>
				<div class="author">by <strong>nemomtt</strong></div>
				<div class="content">In my build, I am thinking of using a lineman's butt set dial.  They are very compact.  I have enclosed some photos.  These dials are likely to have a lot of wear, however, the old butt sets were nearly indestructible.  For instance, they were designed to survive a 20-foot drop test.  I would be interested in Justine's or anyone else's opinion.</div>
			</div>
			<hr />
					<div class="post">
				<h3>Re: Use of lineman's butt set dial.</h3>
				<div class="date">Posted: <strong>Tue Apr 07, 2020 3:04 pm</strong></div>
				<div class="author">by <strong>SteveC</strong></div>
				<div class="content">It's good to know there's another source - thank you. Your pulse switch connections look similar to mine (seem to be many variations). You'll need to cut two flats as shown. I also found it necessary to cut a 1-1.5mm recess near the 9 o'clock position to clear a case pillar. Similarly in the 4 o'clock position, depending how deep the the large 1-2mm semicircle was cut.<br>

<div class="inline-attachment">
			
		
				<dl class="file">
			<dt class="attach-image"><img src="./download/file.php?id=7" class="postimage" alt="dial_10A.jpg" onclick="viewableArea(this);" /></dt>
						<dd>dial_10A.jpg (104.12 KiB) Viewed 3495 times</dd>
		</dl>
		
		
			</div>

* this cut might not be necessary.<br>
<span style="color:#BF0000">Update 29 May: the 2 small cuts are not necessary, simply shave a little off the case internal supports with a sharp knife.</span></div>
			</div>
